      <section id="sde-methodology">
        <h2>Understanding SDE Methodology for Medical Practices</h2>
        <p><strong>Seller's Discretionary Earnings (SDE)</strong> is the gold standard for valuing small to medium-sized medical practices. SDE represents the total financial benefit a single owner-operator would derive from the business, including both salary and discretionary expenses.</p>

        <h3>How SDE is Calculated for Medical Practices</h3>
        <p>For medical practices, SDE calculation includes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Net Income</strong> from practice operations</li>
          <li><strong>Owner's Salary</strong> and benefits</li>
          <li><strong>Discretionary Expenses</strong> (personal use of practice assets)</li>
          <li><strong>Non-recurring Expenses</strong> (one-time costs)</li>
          <li><strong>Depreciation and Amortization</strong> (non-cash expenses)</li>
          <li><strong>Interest Expense</strong> on practice loans</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Why SDE Works for Medical Practices</h3>
        <p>SDE methodology is particularly effective for medical practices because:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>It accounts for the owner's total compensation</li>
          <li>It normalizes for different accounting practices</li>
          <li>It provides a clear picture of cash flow potential</li>
          <li>It's easily comparable across different practice types</li>
        </ul>
